VEREENIGING – Basic Education Minister Angie Motshekga accompanied by Gauteng Education MEC Panyaza Lesufi visited Hoërskool Overvaal in Vereeniging on Monday. This followed skirmishes and rubber bullets outside the school last week over language policy. Minister of Basic Education Angie #Motshekga says they dont want any protesters outside #HoërskoolOvervaal as of tomorrow. She says “respect learners right to an education” @eNCA @eNuus pic.twitter.com/GEKShJOu7D Protester outside #HoërskoolOvervaal says “We don’t get instruction from the minister, we get instruction from our political party, and we will be back tomorrow, and every day after that until Friday. @eNCA MEC #Lesufi says role players in the education department had a productive meeting in the hopes of ending the ongoing protests at #HoërskoolOvervaal @eNCA @eNuus pic.twitter.com/B0q7XzZZSq #Motshekga addresses #HoërskoolOvervaal pupils following a meeting with the school and other role players regarding the ongoing protests at the school @eNCA @eNuus eNuus @DBE_SA pic.twitter.com/nLx2uainGG There was a heavy police presence at the school on Monday as protestors gathered for a fourth academic day to voice their frustration. Last week, a number of protestors were arrested outside the facility for public violence following clashes. A police van was also allegedly petrol bombed by the protestors. READ: Questions asked about education department's role in Overvaal drama Tensions erupted after a court last week ruled that the Afrikaans medium school did not have to accept 55 English-speaking pupils. Monday's meeting with stakeholders was set to take place behind closed doors and education officials were expected to give an update later. eNCA